origins: From the practice in US colleges of numbering courses, the initial (introductory) course commonly being numbered "101".
From Latin quārtō, ablative case singular of quārtus (“fourth”).
It is a tryptamine with a hydroxyl group attached to the carbon atom that is numbered as 5.
From the date September 11 written in numbers according the format used in the United States, which puts the month before the day.
Borrowed from French éclat, from éclater (“to burst out”). Akin to Old English slītan (“to split”). More at slice, slit. Doublet of slate and slat.
The Old English rune ᛟ was sometimes transcribed with the œ ligature.
